    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="app.html" title="click for starting RYT">Roll Your
    Tasks (RYT)</a> (click link for start) is a browser based task management application for
    individuals and small groups.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>It runs with Javascript capable browsers, e.g.
        <ul>
          <li>Firefox (used for development),</li>
          <li>Chrome,</li>
          <li>Safari;</li>
        </ul>
        but it seems to be that Internet Explorer does <em>not</em> work.
      </li>
      <li>Project data will be stored locally and at server for
        <ul>
          <li>sharing projects between different hosts, and</li>
          <li>working offline.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Much more info is available
        <ul>
          <li>by
          <a href="http://www.evolgo.de/RYT_Screencast/MaryNPeterConflictResolution_1.mov">screencast 1</a>,
          <a href="http://www.evolgo.de/RYT_Screencast/MaryNPeterConflictResolution_2.mov">screencast 2</a> and
          <a href="http://www.evolgo.de/RYT_Screencast/MaryNPeterConflictResolution_3.mov">screencast 3</a>,
          which are showing you first steps with RYT; and
          </li>
          <li>by the <em>[info]</em> project, which should be
            loaded automatically after first start of RYT.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Unminified version</h3>
      <p>
        There is an <a href="app_unminified.html" title="click for starting RYT">unminified version</a>, too.
      </p>
    <hr>
    <h2>License Jungle: how to publish?</h2>
    <p>
      There has been an article <a href="">Dangerous Javascript???</a> by R. F. Stallman (FSF). This has motivated me to also provide an unminified - functional identical - RYT version. The minified default version has been made, because a colleague of mine has had a very slow internet connection in a train... But I would suggest to further use the minified one.
    </p>
    <p>
      I've used the term 'software as a service' (SAAS) for describing some of RYT's features:
      <ul>
        <li>no software installation needed,</li>
        <li>automatic upgrade,</li>
        <li>usable from different computers,</li>
        <li>data in the 'cloud'.</li>
        <li></li>
      </ul>
      Now I've seen, that the FSF sees SAAS as dangerous for the freedom of the individual person. But how to keep the comfort while at the same time keeping the user data private?
    </p>
    <h3>There is a solution...</h3>
    <p>
      Currently there is an - experimental - feature of encrypting user data <em>before</em> pushing them onto the server. It remains the problem of not using https for communication with the server. I'm providing RYT at my own server costs (not much so far) and currently don't have a use case....
    </p>
    <h2>Feedback</h2>
    <p>Feedback is appreciated. Please use mail via (RYT) <em>?&rarr;Feedback</em> menu. Don't worry: it's an ordinary mailto (no web form).</p>
